The Iphone 11 pro max has helped make my life easy. I decided to get a new Iphone because my older one was outdated. The Iphone 11 pro max is a great investment due to its variety of uses in our everyday lives.  To begin, the Iphone 11 pro max is affordable to everyone. Secondly It comes in multiple color options such as space gray, rose gold, pink, and etc. The speaker of the Iphone 11 pro max compared to the regular Iphone 11 is far louder in volume, but you could make that assumption based on the size difference.  It also comes with a 3-zoom camera, allowing you to zoom in and out. Furthermore the camera allows you to capture pictures in different options for instance, single, burst or spread.  The speed of the phone is second to none so you don‚Äôt have to worry about too many tabs being opened at one time affecting the loading speed. Lastly the durability is far more impressive compared to older iphones allowing the phone to live up to its value. I experienced dropping my phone on the ground, in water, and even sand but the Iphone still remained intact.  The Iphone 11 pro max is a recommendation for everyone throughout the world to have due to its many haptics. I've been using the iPhone 12 Pro Max for a few weeks now and I'm blown away by its performance. The camera is simply amazing, taking stunning photos and videos even in low light conditions. The 6.7-inch Super Retina XDR display is incredibly sharp and vibrant, making it a pleasure to watch movies and play games on. The battery life is also impressive, easily lasting me a full day with heavy usage.The design is sleek and elegant, with a premium feel that matches its price tag. The Ceramic Shield front cover provides added durability and peace of mind. The A14 Bionic chip is lightning fast, making multitasking and running demanding apps a breeze.Overall, I highly recommend the iPhone 12 Pro Max to anyone looking for the ultimate user experience on a smartphone. It's definitely worth the investment.When it comes to high-end smartphones, the iPhone 12 Pro Max is definitely a top contender. Its main competitors are the Samsung Galaxy S21 Ultra and the Google Pixel 5.In terms of camera performance, the iPhone 12 Pro Max and the Galaxy S21 Ultra are both excellent choices. The S21 Ultra has a slightly higher megapixel count and more advanced zoom capabilities, but the iPhone's software processing produces more natural-looking photos. The Pixel 5, on the other hand, has a great camera for its price range but can't quite match the other two in terms of sheer quality.When it comes to display, the iPhone 12 Pro Max and the Galaxy S21 Ultra both feature stunning OLED screens with high resolutions and refresh rates. The Pixel 5 has a good OLED display as well, but its resolution and refresh rate are lower than the other two.In terms of design and build quality, all three phones are well-made and feel premium in the hand. The iPhone 12 Pro Max has a sleek and elegant design with its flat edges and Ceramic Shield front cover. The Galaxy S21 Ultra has a more modern look with its curved edges and matte finish. The Pixel 5 has a simpler design with a plastic back that some may find less appealing.Overall, all three phones are great choices depending on your needs and preferences. The iPhone 12 Pro Max is the best choice for iOS users who want a premium smartphone with a great camera and display. The Galaxy S21 Ultra is the best choice for Android users who want a top-of-the-line phone with advanced camera features. The Pixel 5 is the best choice for those on a budget who still want a great camera and software experience.üëáhttps://amzn.to/3OVqAdJ

I bought the "good" condition model as a non-cracked screen was very important to me but the body being scratched was not a big deal. The product information says the phone should have been well cleaned, the screen has no scratches, and the body shows light scratches barely visible from 12 inches away. The phone was dirty with visible grime that my cursory wipe with an electronics swab easily picked up, it was clearly not cleaned. The phone body was more than a little scratched. It looks like it got swiped hard on the right facing edge on concrete. You can see the exposed aluminum from far away as the color difference is noticeable from the blue color I got. This is not a big deal to me as it's going to be in a case that would hopefully cover that. The screen has clearly been replaced. The screen also has a pressure glare in the upper section that is visible with some backgrounds. The screen being replaced is annoying as the notification for an unknown part can't be dismissed, so you always have a red notification visible when you look at the settings icon. Overall I would not gift it to others but for the price in comparison to other places was still good. It was also missing the charging block that the info said it was supposed to include along with the cable. I knew that I might not get the best when I opted for a "good" phone over an "excellent" condition one. Maybe I should have just spend the extra $44 dollars and got the excellent condition one. For now I am content with my purchase as most of my complaints are "cosmetic" issues for me.

I purchased this iPhone Mini recently (even if not through Amazon). A critical issue keeps coming up that is making me think I've made a mistake. Apple has failed to update to the newest standard of texting. Why? Tim Cook has said "buy your mom an iPhone" if you want texting to work nicely with her.So when I get photos texted in a thread where there is even just a single non-Apple device in the group chat, *all* images comes in as low-res photo in the thread. That is an issue that Apple has forced by refusing to update to the RCS texting standard put in place several years ago. This also means such messages are not encrypted (less important to me, but still annoying).So if you have friends on Android, know that your messages with them are not encrypted and you will only be able to exchange low-res images with them -- and this is Apple's actual decision to make the product worse because they want YOU to put social pressure on your friend to buy an Apple device. This is madness, and at times I'm now finding myself embarrassed to own an iPhone.
